<div><h3>OM 4600 - Operations and Supply Chain Management </h3>  <hr>Operations management involves the efficient use of resources to create goods or services that satisfy the needs of customers and clients. In both the profit and nonprofit sectors, successful management requires economically rational decisions regarding the design and operation of processes that transform such resources into goods or services. The course develops students&#8217; abilities to identify and structure operating problems and to identify appropriate techniques for resolving them. Examples of topics covered include: operations strategy, process analysis, location selection, capacity management and utilization, inventory management, quality management/assurance, project and supply chain management.<br><br><strong>Prerequisites:</strong> <a href="preview_course_nopop.php?catoid=26&coid=86441" onclick="acalogPopup('preview_course.php?catoid=26&coid=86441&print', '3', 770, 530, 'yes');return false;" rel="remote /ajax/preview_course.php?catoid=26&coid=86441&display_options[location]=tooltip&show" id="tt7702" target="_blank">BAN 4500</a><span style="display: none !important">&#160;</span>Â <br><br><strong>Anticipated Terms Offered:</strong> Fall and Spring semesters<br><br><div style="display: none; z-index: 1000;" class="tooltip for_tt7702"></div></div>		</td>
